<br>
But there is also the question of best use here.<br>
<br>
With some of the changes, clerics can make a good case at being able to roll on a CoF.  I'm fairly sure, however, that most of the melee's would be pretty upset at a cleric winning one of the best haste items in the game.  And rightly so.<br>
<br>
The use a bard would get out of Torbin's Eyepatch is similar.  I dont think anyone would question that a bard (or SK for that matter) wouldnt get some use out of this item.  Some will even get quite a bit of use out of it.  However, neither will get anywhere close to the amount of use a pure wis/int caster will.<br>
<br>
Add to that a bard cannot use any form of mana regen and more does not always equal better.  Would you like an addition 150ish mana that will take you 10 minutes to regen...or some AC + random stat which will make you more effective in combat and a better tank?  I dunno about you...but if I were a melee type I'd go for haste/ac over wis/int.<br>
<br>
And at the end of the day, there is this little fact.  And one that has stood the test of time over many many many KCoG raids.<br>
<br>
Cloak of Flames - Lord Nagafen = melees<br>
Torbin's Eyepatch - Lady Vox  = casters <br>
<br>
Each of the 2 dragons will drop a piece of loot that is restricted by class type.  Unless you want to make the CoF rollable for everyone, to balance things out the Eyepatch should be restricted as well.<br>
<br>
As for this being a reason why people wont show up.  I suppose thats possible.  Still...there is the white scale for bards and the book for paladins.<br>
<br>
And after all the loot is settled, the premis for KCoG is not loot or who gets what.  KCoG is about an idea and vision of everyone having the opportunity to do these targets.  It doesnt matter what guild you are from, how long you've played the game, or where you are from.  If you want to see a Dragon or a Plane then KCoG offers that opportunity.<br>
<br>
The loot rules are setup not to encourage people to show up to certain targets, but to ensure a certain amount of fairness in an otherwise unfair world.  KCoG operates on the belief that people will show up even without any other motivation other than a desire to help others and do things they might not otherwise have a chance to do.<br>
<br>
Of course we all play for different reasons.  Thats a good thing.  But since no one can please anyone in an environment that has a limited supply versus demand, the best we can do is try to be fair.  Some people will get screwed in this arrangement.  I would it be otherwise, but unfortunatly its not.  As such the best we can do is promote these events as a fun thing and try to make loot a secondary factor.  So that at least if you have fun you'll have something to take away even if you dont get any hard loot.<br>
<br>
And remember.  One day we'll all leave EQ.  Some sooner, some later.  But eventually everyone will move on.  When that happens what loot you got, what levels you made, what guilds you were in will matter not.  All you'll have is the memories of the raids you were on, the friends you made, and the experiences you had.  Which is, I think, a far more important thing than any loot you can recieve.<br>
<br>
Kellory Silverstar<br>
The Watchmen<br>
KCoG Plane Raid Liason - Retired<br>
&quot;Still the original Crunchy flavor adored by mobs all across Norrath.&quot;<br>
